            data_text:
              "Subject: Your Application for Vice President, Enterprise Sales – ACME                               \n\nDear John,                                                                                          \n\nThank you for taking the time to apply for the Vice President, Enterprise Sales position at ACME. We\nsincerely appreciate your interest in our company and the effort you put into submitting your       \napplication.                                                                                        \n\nAfter carefully reviewing your profile against the requirements of this role, we have determined    \nthat we are unable to move forward with your candidacy at this time. I want to share some specific  \nfeedback so this is as helpful as possible:                                                         \n\nThis position requires a minimum of 12+ years of progressive B2B sales experience, including at     \nleast 5 years in VP-level leadership roles, along with a demonstrated track record of managing      \n$100M+ in annual recurring revenue and building and scaling enterprise sales teams of 50+ people.   \nThe role also demands deep expertise in complex SaaS and enterprise software sales to Fortune 500   \norganizations, with strong executive-level stakeholder engagement.                                  \n\nYour background reflects valuable experience in retail sales and customer service, and your         \nachievements — such as earning Employee of the Month recognition and contributing to visual         \nmerchandising and team training — speak to your strong work ethic and interpersonal skills. However,\nyour experience is currently oriented toward entry-level retail and consumer-facing roles, and the  \nposition requires extensive enterprise technology sales leadership, B2B revenue accountability, and \norganizational management at a senior executive level. These are fundamental differences in         \nindustry, seniority, and skill set that we were unable to bridge for this particular opportunity.   \n\nThat said, your customer-facing strengths and design background are genuine assets. I would         \nencourage you to explore roles that align more closely with your graphic design education and your  \nstated passion for apparel and retail, where your unique combination of creative and sales skills   \ncould truly shine. Building experience in B2B environments over time could also open doors to       \nprogressively senior commercial roles in the future.                                                \n\nWe wish you every success in your career journey, and we encourage you to keep an eye on            \nopportunities at ACME that may be a stronger fit as your career evolves.                            \n\nWarm regards,                                                                                       \n\n[Your Name] [Your Title] Talent Acquisition, ACME                                                   \n",
            data_html:
              "Subject: Your Application for Vice President, Enterprise Sales – ACME\n\nDear John,\n\nThank you for taking the time to apply for the Vice President, Enterprise Sales position at ACME. We sincerely appreciate your interest in our company and the effort you put into submitting your application.\n\nAfter carefully reviewing your profile against the requirements of this role, we have determined that we are unable to move forward with your candidacy at this time. I want to share some specific feedback so this is as helpful as possible:\n\nThis position requires a minimum of **12+ years of progressive B2B sales experience**, including at least **5 years in VP-level leadership roles**, along with a demonstrated track record of **managing $100M+ in annual recurring revenue** and **building and scaling enterprise sales teams of 50+ people**. The role also demands deep expertise in **complex SaaS and enterprise software sales** to Fortune 500 organizations, with strong executive-level stakeholder engagement.\n\nYour background reflects valuable experience in **retail sales and customer service**, and your achievements — such as earning Employee of the Month recognition and contributing to visual merchandising and team training — speak to your strong work ethic and interpersonal skills. However, your experience is currently oriented toward entry-level retail and consumer-facing roles, and the position requires extensive enterprise technology sales leadership, B2B revenue accountability, and organizational management at a senior executive level. These are fundamental differences in industry, seniority, and skill set that we were unable to bridge for this particular opportunity.\n\nThat said, your customer-facing strengths and design background are genuine assets. I would encourage you to explore roles that align more closely with your **graphic design education** and your stated passion for **apparel and retail**, where your unique combination of creative and sales skills could truly shine. Building experience in B2B environments over time could also open doors to progressively senior commercial roles in the future.\n\nWe wish you every success in your career journey, and we encourage you to keep an eye on opportunities at ACME that may be a stronger fit as your career evolves.\n\nWarm regards,\n\n[Your Name]\n[Your Title]\nTalent Acquisition, ACME",
